And as such we have to consider the idea of why a corporation like Disney would want to become a dominant part of our identities, and what can happen if we let that happen.

So yeah...in summary, when we talk about "disney adults" we often blame the individuals for brand worship, but I think, more than anything, that the real issue is that this level of brand worship doesn't happen unless a company wants it and really goes after it. https://t.co/VayAz2iAVZ

The money at the top is not why you love those things. Lion King is not Lion King because of the Walt Disney Corporation, it’s Lion King because of the talented staff involved. And yet we associate it with the mouse more…meaning they can claim it’s identity and meaning to us.

Like think about how entangled the brand of “Disney” is with the media it’s produced unlike any other studio. There’s no “Warner Bros adults,” no one says “oh I’m a huge Paramount fan, I love Spongebob.” Disney is trying to build a cultural worship first and foremost.

The discourse surrounding “Disney adults” always tends to ignore a real terrifying element I think: Disney is attempting to position its brand as an inherent part of culture and important part of our lives, rather than the reality: it’s the money behind the things we like.

I've been in digital spaces with friends from far away, I enjoy it...but we always end up saying we wish we could be there in person. I don't want a projection of them next to me, I want to feel them next to me. Trying to sell us a cheap imitation of that is wholly detrimental.

These advancements in VR could be great for many things, but do not let them distract you from the fact that this shouldn't be our entire lives. That what the future should be is making travel easier and safer, and making it so we can be with people more often.

You cannot feel the warmth of someone next to you, you can't feel their hugs or hold their hand, you cannot exist in that same space of senses and experience it fully together. And the idea that they want to make those things harder so they can sell it back to us disturbs me.

And a big part of that is reselling you the physical experiences of living...and I have to say its an awful sell. Because there's a reason we all got zoom fatigue...and that's because there are intangibles to in person social relations that video calls nor VR cannot solve.

The metaverse's stated goal is to become the new interface for the internet, and its goal is to become the platform through which we experience all of life. To monetize what had to be done physically, and make it done digitally through platforms they control.

Alright, I don’t think anyone saw the Bengals here…or in the playoffs…or doing good at all. But while they have holes it isn’t unprecedented when broken down. It makes sense, they’re extremely well built in terms of an even defensive fit.

Have we built a more equal society, or one where we root for teams under a label? Do they understand each other as humans or just want to be the alpha...we should care less about the label and more about the ideals and actions because that makes a more tangible sustainable future

A society built on spin and these charisma based arguments can result in a few more people adopting a label and maybe voting for an idea attached to that label, but society is more than labels. How have we as a society grown better in that "winning"?

And when you are more focused on controlling audience reaction to "win", your concern will not be what is accurate, but how to win people over. Which I think is hollow and doesn't form a long term growth. I think our society should not be about winning, but rather educating.

Why even have the conversation if your only goal is to project a vision of confidence and power? At that point you aren't proving or disproving anything because the only way you win is by controlling the crowd. I much prefer we discuss the ideas with confidence in their validity.

One last tweet about the debate thing: the reason why I object to the current construction of debate streams is very simple: they are often done with moderators and without fact checkers on standby, and thus are all about confidence and rhetoric. I don't find value in that.

Sure the director plays roles in all of the similar stuff but they also oversee everyone. The cinematographer is thus the expert on site for simply the lighting and camera component.

It’s why you can often credit the director and cinematographer together. For an image to work they have to communicate and work together. The director has ideas and general know how, the cinematographer is a high class technical that can translate that into what’s wanted.

So for cinematography that’d mean working with the lighting crew, directly proposing ideas for camera placement, finding the technicals of the camera, trying different lenses. The director composes a general look of the images…the cinematographer finalizes it.

If a writer composes a script, and the director conducts it into image with their ideas, then in the symphony metaphor the cinematographer is like…the highest level of sound guy in a symphony performance. They take into account reverb, how the orchestra performs, mixing, etc.

For non-film people I think you need to know that cinematography is a very specific part of the process. Like it’s by far one of the most complicated and impressive parts of the process, but it’s also more minimal in the final cut than you think.

Approaching film and film criticism as a category you can win isn’t the point. That’s textbook pretension. The goal is to get your audience to understand you and your reaction on that emotional level. It’s why even a review you agree with can still be good. Be emotionally honest.

You can be funny, harsh, cynical, but you have to approach it as your own emotional state. You are painting a canvas with how a piece of art made you feel, and as such the best criticism is one that is an honest attempt to express them fully. You cannot be the best at that.

My issue is and has always been viewing movies as a form to conquer. To be better than. To be the best AT watching the movies. And I HATE that approach. The thing that’s beautiful about art, including movies AND criticism, is that it uses its form to present honest emotion…
